A look at AidData’s updated dataset on Chinese development finance activities

library(knitr)
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
library(kableExtra)
library(DT)

Credit: A city park in Tianjin, China. Photo: Yang Aijun / World Bank

China has provided foreign assistance to countries around the world since the 1950s. Since it’s not part of the DAC group of donors who report their activities in a standard manner, there isn’t an official dataset which breaks down where Chinese foreign assistance goes, and what it’s used for.

A team of researchers at AidData, in the College of William and Mary have just updated their “Chinese Global Official Finance” dataset. This is an unofficial compilation of over 4,000 Chinese-financed projects in 138 countries, from 2000 to 2014, based on a triangulation of public data from government systems, public records and media reports. The team have coded these projects with over 50 variables which help identify and group projects by different characteristics.

Activity-level data, but a partial picture of total financial flows

This dataset is interesting for two reasons. First, China and other emerging donors are making an impact on the development finance landscape. As the Bank has reported in the past (see International Debt Statistics 2016), bilateral creditors are a more important source of finance than they were just five years ago. And the majority of these increases are coming from emerging donors with China playing a prominent role.

Second, this dataset’s project-level data on China’s bilateral support offers a window into the relative trends and allocations of Chinese foreign assistance that can inform further analysis and research. Organizations like the World Bank collect detailed data directly from government sources, but the Bank is unable to make these data publicly available. Our financial flow statistics are typically only disaggregated by class or groups of creditors, not by individual counterparties or at an activity-level. So there can be value added from sources such as AidData’s China dataset.

But users should bear in mind that this data offers a partial picture. AidData’s China dataset only presents estimates of official bilateral credits - just one part of the total financial flows from China. The Bank is able to integrate the granular data it collects from countries into the full set of financial flows to and from its borrowing countries. This situates official bilateral credit among the broader spectrum of providers of long-term financing (such as bondholders, financial intermediaries, and other private sector entities), sources of short-term debt (including movements in bank deposits), and equity investments (foreign direct and portfolio investments). This data integration leads to better quality statistics.

In short, the AidData’s China dataset provides more detail, but is likely to be less reliable for a number of low-income countries. With these caveats in mind, I have done a quick exploration of the dataset to produce some summary statistics and give you an idea of what’s inside. This post is written as an R Notebook which means you see the code behind the charts and anlysis, and you can download and run the whole document to do your own analysis.

# Read in the dataset
chinaData <- read_excel("aiddata-china-dataset.xlsx", sheet = "AidData_ChinaGlobal_Data")

Looking at foreign assistance by type of flow

First, let’s see what the trends in differnt types of foreign assistance look like. AidData researchers code the projects they’ve identified into three types of “flow”:

  1. Official Development Assistance (ODA), which contains a grant element of 25% or more and is primarily intended for developmet
  2. Other Official Flows (OOF), where the grant element is under 25% and the the financing more commercial
  3. Vague Official Finance, where there isn’t enough information to assign it to either category.
# group data by year & flow type, summarize totals expressed in USD deflated to 2014, convert to billions and round 
dfp <- chinaData %>%
  filter(recommended_for_research == "TRUE") %>%
  group_by(year,flow_class) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(usd_defl_2014, na.rm="TRUE")) %>%
  mutate(total = round(total/1e9,2))
#
# plot amount by year and facet by flow type
#
p <- ggplot(dfp, aes(year,total)) +
  # geom_bar(stat="identity",  aes(fill=flow_class)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill ="#38b1ef" ) +
  facet_wrap(~flow_class) +
  #scale_x_discrete(limits=c(2000,2014)) +
  ylab(label = "Billions (USD 2014)") +
  theme(legend.position="none", axis.title.x = element_blank()) +
  labs(title="Chinese Official Finance by Flow Type (2000-2014)", 
       caption="Source: AidData. 2017. Global Chinese Official Finance Dataset")
p

It looks like more Chinese finance is classed as OOF ($216bn in the period above) than ODA ($81bn), and that 2009 is a bit of an outlier. Let’s figure out which countries are the top recipients of ODA and OFA and also which sectors are most financed. But first, let’s see what accounts for the spike in 2009. At a guess, it’s going to be some large individual projects coded that year, so let’s look for anything > $10bn.

dfa <- chinaData %>%
  filter(recommended_for_research == "TRUE" & year==2009 & flow_class=='OOF-like') %>%
  mutate(amount = round(usd_defl_2014/1e9,1)) %>%
  filter(amount > 10)
datatable(dfa[c('project_id','title','amount')], 
  options=list(searching=FALSE,paging=FALSE,bInfo=FALSE), 
  rownames=FALSE)


It looks like some of the large jump can be explained by two large projects involving Russian energy firms Transneft and Roseneft which - they’re also referenced in this 2009 Reuters article about China loaning Russia $25 billion to access to 20 years of oil. This is a good example of why having an activity-level breakdown of the data is so useful.

Who are the top recipients of ODA and OOF?

Switching back to an aggregate view - which countries have received the most ODA and OOF in the 15 years the dataset covers?

# TODO - calculate and add bars for top countries ODA/OOF
#These are the project status codes AidData recommend for use when aggregating. We're going to sum by 
aggregationStatus <- c('Completion', 'Implementation', 'Pipeline: Commitment')
#Top10 ODA
chODAtop10 <- chinaData %>%
  filter(umbrella=='0' & flow_class=='ODA-like') %>%
  filter(status %in% aggregationStatus) %>%
  group_by(recipient_condensed) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(usd_defl_2014, na.rm="TRUE")) %>%
  mutate(total = round(total/1e9,1)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  top_n(10)
#Top10 OOF
chOOFtop10 <- chinaData %>%
  filter(umbrella=='0' & flow_class=='OOF-like') %>%
  filter(status %in% aggregationStatus) %>%
  group_by(recipient_condensed) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(usd_defl_2014, na.rm="TRUE")) %>%
  mutate(total = round(total/1e9,1)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  top_n(10)
#Build ODA Plot
ODA <- ggplot(chODAtop10, aes(x=reorder(recipient_condensed,total),y=total)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill ="#38b1ef") + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 40)) +
  labs(title="Top 10 Countries for \"Official Development Assistance\" from China", 
       subtitle="Total for period 2000 - 2014 (USD 2014)",
       caption="Source: AidData. 2017. Global Chinese Official Finance Dataset")  +
  geom_text(data=chODAtop10, aes(x=recipient_condensed,y=total,label=paste(total,"bn")), nudge_y = 2) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank())
#Build ODA Plot
OOF <- ggplot(chOOFtop10, aes(x=reorder(recipient_condensed,total),y=total)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill ="#38b1ef") + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 40)) +
  labs(title="Top 10 Countries for \"Other Official Flows\"from China", 
       subtitle="Total for period 2000 - 2014 (USD 2014)",
       caption="Source: AidData. 2017. Global Chinese Official Finance Dataset")  +
  geom_text(data=chOOFtop10, aes(x=recipient_condensed,y=total,label=paste(total,"bn")), nudge_y = -2.5) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank())
ODA

OOF


This again shows the relative difference in size of ODA vs OOF but also throws some surprises - did you know Cuba was China’s largest recipient of bilateral aid?

Which sectors receive the most investment via ODA or OOF?

Finally, let’s take a look by sector - the AidData team have coded projects using DAC Sector Codes and we can look at the relative allocation of resources across these sectors by flow type:

TODO: chart sector variations by ODA/OOF

chs <- chinaData %>%
  filter(recommended_for_research == "TRUE") %>%
  group_by(flow_class,crs_sector_name) %>%
  summarise(total=sum(usd_defl_2014, na.rm="TRUE")) %>%
  mutate(total = round(total/1e9,2)) %>%
  spread(flow_class,total) 
#get ~the top 4 sectors and group everything else into "other"
oof <- chs[c(1,3)]
oda <- chs[c(1,2)] 
ooftot <- colSums(oof[2],na.rm = TRUE)
odatot <- colSums(oda[2],na.rm = TRUE)
toof <- head(oof[order(-chs$`OOF-like`),],4)
toda <- head(oda[order(-chs$`ODA-like`),][c(1:3,5),],4)
tooftot <- colSums(toof[2],na.rm = TRUE)
todatot <- colSums(toda[2],na.rm = TRUE)
oofother <- ooftot - tooftot
odaother <- odatot - todatot
toof <- rbind(toof,c("Other",oofother))
toda <- rbind(toda,c("Other",odaother))
datatable(chs, 
  options=list(searching=FALSE,paging=TRUE), 
  rownames=FALSE)
